  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 28.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - We learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 5:4, 5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that David was thirty years old when he began to reign in Hebron. He must, therefore, have died in his seventy-first year. That this is called here a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "good old age",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " shows that the length of human life had now greatly subsided. In comparison of all his successors on the thrones of Judah and of Israel, his age was clearly a \"good old age?' 1 Chronicles 29:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
